I'm not sure which version of Confluence I have, but I have a lot of tables in Word documents that I need to put on a Wiki. The best way that I've found is to save the document as a web page and then get the HTML code and use the HTML macro. This is working and keeps the proper formatting, however, after I use the HTML macro, I am not able to add anymore text after it in Wiki Markup. I've tried making a seperate page to use the HTML macro on and then use an include statement, but I have the same problem. Please feel free to let me know if there is a better way to convert the tables in Word to a Wiki or if there is a way to add text after using the HTML macro.

A customer pointed out the following:

{quote}A bunch of scripts in confluence/bin/ need to be executable, and they do have the executable bit for the file owner out-of-the-tarball. But the group and world execute bits are missing, which causes one extra manual step at install/upgrade time in tightened setups where the confluence user does not own the scripts in bin (there's no need for the user to own them). The JIRA tarballs do not have this problem, they do have the needed executable bits for user, group, and world. The fix for the confluence tarball should be simple:

{{find bin -type f -perm +111 -print0 | xargs -0 chmod +x}}

In other words, scripts that need executable permissions should have them {{rwxr-xr-x}} straight out of the tarball instead of the current {{rwxr--r--}} .

Related earlier reports and discussion: CONF-6367, JRA-12967, http://forums.atlassian.com/message.jspa?messageID=257241034{quote}

